tridb_operator_arg_hardening.patch — advisor plan 024: harden tjs()/tjs_open() entry points
and memory lifecycle. Applies LAST in the chain, after tridb_tjs_filter_first.patch.

  (1) Argument validation: tjs k 1..10000; tjs_open k/m_seeds 1..10000, hops 1..8 (the old
      silent 0->default coercions for m_seeds/hops are now ERRORs). k=0 previously hit
      top()/pop() on an EMPTY std::priority_queue (UB/SIGSEGV); negative k arrived through
      PG_GETARG_UINT32 as ~4.29e9 (unbounded "bounded" heap).
  (2) Eviction frees: every bounded-PQ eviction heap_freetuple's the evicted copy (and
      fetchBridgeRowsO frees a rejected new copy), making the O(batch + k) peak-memory
      comment true. Result tuples (final unspool / finalizeTopKO chosen set) are NEVER freed.
  (3) Error-path memory release: a MemoryContextCallback on the SRF's multi-call context
      releases the malloc'd state + new'd C++ containers on abort (ereport longjmps past
      EndTJSState/EndTJSOpenState). free(state) happens ONLY in the callback — the callback
      node is embedded in the struct, so freeing earlier would dangle the context's
      reset-callback list. The callback never touches executor/SPI/relation teardown.
  (4) snprintf truncation guards at all 4 previously-unchecked compose sites (silent
      truncation could drop a trailing `and (<filter>)` — wrong rows).

FUTURE OPERATORS MUST COPY the arg-guard + release-callback pattern.
Sentinel (both files): TRIDB: operator arg hardening
